    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Δι<hi rend="ligature">οσ</hi>κόροις <supplied reason="subaudible">ἀνέθηκε</supplied> εὐχὴν 
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Lucius Λούκιος">Λούκιος</name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Velleius Οὐήλιος">Οὐήλιος</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Fronto Φρόντων">Φρόντ<hi rend="ligature">ων</hi></name></persName>.
                </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>"To the Dioskoroi, Lucius Vel(l)eius Fronto [dedicated] (this) offering."</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text records an offering to the Dioskoroi by Lucius Velleius Fronto. Such
                    offerings were found in large quantities during archaeological excavation of
                    Pisidia, all in similar rectangular reliefs and many containing the eagle and
                    the woman, though the identity of the woman is debated since the extant
                    inscriptions only name the Dioskoroi. While the name of Lucius Velleius Fronto
                    seems elsewhere unattested, the clear Roman name suggests a date no earlier than
                    established Roman presence in the region around the first century CE.
                    Additionally, the praenomina of Lucius is often found with the gentilicium of
                    Velleius after the second century CE. </p></div>
            

